*        1. Python or Pip is Completely Missing / Command Not Found
* If typing python3 or pip3 gives you a "command not found" error, the system packages might be missing.
* Bash
* 
* # 1. Update your package lists first
* sudo apt update
* 
* # 2. Install Python3, Pip, and the Venv module all at once
* sudo apt install python3 python3-pip python3-venv -y
* 
* # 3. Check where they are installed
* which python3
* which pip3
* Why: Ubuntu and Kali sometimes ship minimal installations. You need to explicitly tell the apt package manager to fetch the core Python tools.
* 2. The "venv" Module is Missing (Exit Status 1)
* If you try to run python3 -m venv venv and it fails saying the module is not found or throws an error.
* Bash
* 
* # 1. Install the specific venv package (often separated in Debian/Ubuntu)
* sudo apt install python3-venv -y
* 
* # 2. Try creating the environment again
* python3 -m venv venv
* 
* # 3. Activate it
* source venv/bin/activate
* Why: In Debian-based systems (like Kali and Ubuntu), the venv module isn't always bundled with the base python3 package to save space. You have to install it separately.
* 3. Pip is Broken, Missing, or Failing Inside an Environment
* If your environment activates, but pip throws traceback errors or isn't found.
* Bash
* 
* # 1. Try forcing Python to bootstrap pip natively
* python3 -m ensurepip --upgrade
* 
* # 2. If ensurepip fails, download the official repair script
* wget https://bootstrap.pypa.io/get-pip.py
* 
* # 3. Run the repair script (make sure your venv is activated if repairing a venv!)
* python3 get-pip.py
* 
* # 4. Verify it works
* python3 -m pip --version
* Why: Sometimes virtual environments build improperly, or system updates break the pip binaries. The get-pip.py script bypasses the broken binaries and pulls a fresh, working copy directly from the Python Package Authority.
* 4. "Externally Managed Environment" Error (The PEP 668 Block)
* If you are on modern Kali Linux (2023.1+) or Ubuntu 23.04+ and try to run pip install requests outside of a virtual environment, you will get a massive red error saying "error: externally-managed-environment".
* You have three ways to bypass this during an exam:
* Option A: The Proper Way (Virtual Environment)
* Bash
* 
* python3 -m venv venv
* source venv/bin/activate
* pip install requests
* Option B: The Debian Way (Use APT instead of PIP) Instead of using pip, use the system package manager to install the Python library.
* Bash
* 
* sudo apt install python3-requests
* Option C: The "CTF Speed" Way (Force it) If you are in a rush and don't care about breaking your system Python packages (which is fine for a disposable exam VM), you can override the block.
* Bash
* 
* pip install requests --break-system-packages
* Why: Linux distributions recently locked down global pip installs to stop users from accidentally breaking OS-level tools that rely on Python. --break-system-packages tells the OS to ignore the safety rails.
* 5. General Maintenance & Sanity Checks
* If scripts are acting weird or you suspect a version mismatch.
* Bash
* 
* # See exactly which Python version is active
* python3 --version
* 
* # See exactly which pip you are using (Is it global? Is it in a venv?)
* pip3 -V
* 
* # List all installed packages in your current environment
* pip3 list
* 
* # Deactivate a virtual environment when you are done
* deactivate
